Why we need it in webpack, why we need browser API on webpack side? Why don't use `currentScript`

Also look at your code, you have `script` type and wait `import.meta.url` will work (we don't polyfill your code)? You can install the latest version of `webpack` and use:
```
module: {
        parser: {
            javascript: {
                importMeta: false
            }
        }
    },
```

It will keep `import.meta.url` as is, but you need to switch to ESM, otherwise `currentScript` is workaround, alternative - you can implement own plugin for webpack, but I don't think you are looking for this.

Here my example of polyfill:
```
const import_meta_url =
  typeof document === 'undefined' ? new URL('file:' + __filename).href :
    (document.currentScript && document.currentScript.src || new URL('main.js', document.baseURI).href);
```

Script in UserScripts are loaded using the UserScript header which looks like in the example attached in the original post:
```javascript
// ==UserScript==
// @name tw-command-sender
// @version 1.1.0
// @description Automatic command sender for the Tribal Wars game
// @author szelbi
// @match *://*/*
// @require https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/luxon@2.3.0
// @grant unsafeWindow
// ==/UserScript==
```

The `@require` statement "points to a JavaScript file that is loaded and executed before the script itself starts running", as described here: https://www.tampermonkey.net/documentation.php#_require

I am generating the header using the webpack plugin and those `@require` statements are based on the content of the `externals` section in the webpack configuration. If a script is there, it is attached in the UserScript header.  
You can check the code of the plugin in the repo attached in the original post in the `plugins/userscript.ts` path.

