Thank you so much to @alexander-akait , I have been able to follow the logic and recreate the way css-loader generates a class name hash for CSS modules by default.

1. The string which is being hashed consists of the path, file name, unprintable character and the class name
2. This string is hashed using md4
3. This hash is base64 encoded
4. If the resulting string starts with a number, an underscore is prepended
5. Forward slashes are replaced with dashes.

Early POC this PHP appears to recreate the generated class names : 
```
class ClassName
{
    private $path = 'public/content/themes/brickblocks/modules/components/card/';
    private $file = 'style.module.scss';
    private $sep = "\x00";

    public function generateClass($class)
    {
        // Build the string to hash
        $string =  "{$this->path}{$this->file}{$this->sep}{$class}";

        // Generate a hash
        $hash = hash('md4', $string, true);

        // Encode it for easier use on the web
        $base64 = base64_encode($hash);

        // HTML class names cannot start with a number
        $fstchar = substr($base64, 0, 1);
        if (is_numeric($fstchar)) {
            $base64 = '_' . $base64; // Add an underscore
        }

        // Forward slashes get replaces with a dash.
        $base64 = str_replace('/', '-', $base64);

        return $base64;
    }
}
```

